surveys.narrative: Blacksmith Lake is a small, 37 acre coldwater lake located seventeen miles north of Park Rapids in Hubbard County. Blacksmith Lake is a designated trout lake and is stocked annually with 5,600 rainbow trout fingerlings. Blacksmith Lake is open to fishing during the summer trout season only. No winter-time angling is allowed. A unimproved county access is located on the west shore of the lake. The entire shoreline is county tax-forfeited land with two leased cabins on the lake.Good numbers of rainbow trout were sampled during the 2005 survey (10.5 trout/gillnet). Sampled rainbow trout ranged in length from 10.9 to 18.5 inches, with an average length and weight of 13.5 inches and 1.2 pounds. Rainbow trout gillnet catch rates in previous surveys have ranged from 4.0 trout/gillnet (1984, 1995) to 17.5 trout/gillnet (1987).
The rainbow trout population appears to be above average for trout lakes in this area.
The net catch of rainbow trout was lower than in 1987, but still indicated a fair population.

Population assessment was conducted to assess the fish population in Black Smith Lake, in anticipation of a proposed reclaimation for the fall of 1972.Black Smith Lake has no history of any type of fisheries management of any kind. I think the main reason is that there has been no developed road to the lake until recently. This lake is located within Hubbard County tax forfeit land. There is one hunting lease located on the west shore of the lake, which has a cabin located on it. The fellow who has the lease said he would be happy to make a good landing on the southwest shore with a bulldozer which he owns. The road that goes to the lake now ends at a steep decline to the lake. I have talked to the County Commissioners in regards to this project, and they are 100% in favor of it. The only thing that will have to be done is to get a permit from the Hubbard County Board of Appeals in order to make an access and parking lot.

Blacksmith Lake is a small, 37 acre coldwater lake located seventeen miles north of Park Rapids in Hubbard County. Blacksmith Lake is a designated trout lake and is stocked with rainbow trout fingerlings every fall. Blacksmith Lake is open to fishing during the summer trout season only. No winter-time angling is allowed.Rainbow trout were sampled in moderate numbers (4.0/gillnet). Size of rainbow trout was good, with an average length of 13.5 inches and 1.2 lbs, which is a very acceptable size for anglers. Rainbow trout up to 15.7 inches were sampled. The two previous surveys had much higher gillnet catches: 8.5/net in 1990 and 17.5/net in 1987. The gillnet catch in 1984 was the same as in 1995 (4.0/gillnet). The only other species sampled were golden shiner (3.2/trapnet) and one walleye (0.5/gillnet). No walleyes have been sampled in previous surveys. The walleye sampled could have come from walleye rearing ponds located within the Blacksmith Lake watershed, or from an unauthorized stocking.

Blacksmith Lake is a small, 37 acre coldwater lake located seventeen miles north of Park Rapids in Hubbard County. Blacksmith lake is a designated trout lake and is stocked annually with 5,600 rainbow trout fingerlings. Blacksmith Lake is open to fishing during the summer trout season only. No winter-time angling is allowed. A county-owned public access is located on the west shore of the lake. The entire shoreline is county tax-forfeited land with two leased cabins on the lake. Rainbow trout were sampled in high numbers during the 2000 survey (17.0 trout/gillnet). Sampled rainbow trout ranged in length from 10.2 to 17.7 inches with an average length and weight of 12.5 inches and 0.8 pounds. Rainbow trout gillnet catch rates in previous surveys have ranged from 4.0 trout/gillnet (1984, 1995) to 17.5 trout/gillnet (1987). Golden shiner and one walleye were the only other species sampled. The walleye was likely caught from a surrounding lake and put into Blacksmith.

Blacksmith Lake has a surface area of 38.5 acres, a shoreline length of 1.36 miles, and a maximum depth of 45 feet. A county owned public access is located on the northwest corner of the lake. Blacksmith lake is one of three lakes in the Park Rapids Management Area designated as a stream-trout lake, specifically managed for rainbow trout, and is stocked each fall with rainbow trout. The other two lakes are Newman and Crappie Lakes.

In 2013, abundance of rainbow trout was the highest ever. Fish from the 2012 stocking were 7 to 10.5 inches and fish from the 2011 stockings were 12 to 16 inches.

Blacksmith Lake is one of three lakes in the Park Rapids Management Area designated as a stream trout lake, specifically managed for Rainbow Trout, and stocked each fall with Rainbow Trout fingerlings. The other two lakes are Newman and Crappie Lakes.

Abundance of Rainbow Trout in 2021 was the highest ever recorded at Blacksmith Lake. Fish from the 2020 stocking were 7 to 11 inches and fish from the 2019 and 2018 stockings were 12 to 16 inches.

Blacksmith Lake is a small, 37 acre coldwater lake located seventeen miles north of Park Rapids in Hubbard County. Blacksmith is a designated trout lake and is stocked each fall with 5,600 rainbow trout fingerlings. Blacksmith is open to fishing during the summer trout season only, no winter-time angling is allowed. An unimproved county access is located on the west shore of the lake. The entire shoreline is county tax-forfeited land with two leased cabins on the lake.

Rainbow trout abundance was down, with the gillnet catch rate of 2.0 trout/gillnet the lowest recorded for all surveys since 1984 and well below the current management goal of 10.0 trout/gillnet. Rainbow trout abundance was higher in the two previous surveys in 2000 (17.0 trout/gillnet) and 2005 (10.5 trout/gillnet). Sampled rainbow trout ranged in length from 4.9 to 15.7 inches. Golden shiner were sampled in very high numbers (29.0 golden shiner/trapnet). Golden shiner have been sampled in low to moderate numbers in past surveys, but their abundance has increased substantially since the 2005 survey. There is a concern that the abundant golden shiner population could be impacting the trout population by competing for food with fingerling trout.

Blacksmith Lake is located twelve miles north of Park Rapids in central Hubbard County. Blacksmith Lake has a surface area of 38.5 acres, a shoreline length of 1.36 miles, and a maximum depth of 45 feet. A county owned public access is located on the northwest corner of the lake, which can be difficult for larger boat trailers. Blacksmith Lake is one of three lakes in the Park Rapids Fisheries Management Area designated as a stream trout lake and stocked each fall with Rainbow Trout fingerlings. The other two lakes are Newman and Crappie Lakes.

Abundance of Rainbow Trout in 2017 was the highest ever recorded at Blacksmith Lake. Fish from the 2016 stocking were 8 to 11 inches and fish from previous stockings were 12 to 20 inches. Eighty-seven percent of the captured Rainbow Trout in 2017 were Kamloops. Based on results of higher survival of Kamloops than Arlee strain from the Study IV project, all Rainbow Trout stocking will consist of Kamloops strain starting in 2017.
